def NewFigure(sizeCol=12, sizeRow=6):
    return plt.figure(figsize=(sizeCol, sizeRow))

def DisplaySub(fig, countRow,countCol,index,image,title='',
               axis='off',cmap=None):
    ax=fig.add_subplot(countRow, countCol, index)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.axis(axis)
    plt.imshow(image,cmap=cmap)
    return ax

Load training dataset¶

We use the data provided by Udacity for training of the SVM classifier.

The data consist of two classes, namely 'vehicles' and 'non-vehicles', with sample size of 8792 and 8968 respectively.

In addition, we also manually created some hard negative samples from misclassifications of the SVM classifier during early attempts. This notebook does not cover the details regarding the generation of these hard negative samples. In essence, 73 such samples are identified manually, and then data augmentation, including 4 variations in image smoothing and 5 variations in extent of white noise added are introduced (73 x 4 x 5 = 1460 augmented image generated). In total, 73 + 1460 = 1533 hard negative samples are added to the training dataset.

Feature extraction functions¶

We will be using Histogram of Oriented Gradient (HOG) as the primary input feature of our classifier. HOG features in essence capture the direction information of edge gradients among image patches. It is thus useful in capturing shape related information.

We will also use two additional image features, i.e. color histogram and spatial binning of color image, to complement the HOG features.

Below are some utility functions for extracting these image features.

In [4]:
def convert_color(img, conv='RGB'):
    if conv == 'RGB':
        return img
    if conv == 'YCrCb':
        return cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_RGB2YCrCb)
    if conv == 'HSV':
        return cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_RGB2HSV)
    if conv == 'HLS':
        return cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_RGB2HLS)
    if conv == 'LAB':
        return cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_RGB2LAB)
    if conv == 'LUV':
        return cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_RGB2LUV)
    if conv == 'YUV':
        return cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_RGB2YUV)
    if conv == 'GRAY':
        return cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_RGB2GRAY)

def bin_spatial(img, size=(32, 32), vis=False):
    resized = cv2.resize(img, size)
    if len(resized.shape)==3:
        color1 = resized[:,:,0].ravel()
        color2 = resized[:,:,1].ravel()
        color3 = resized[:,:,2].ravel()
        if vis==True:
            return resized, color1, color2, color3, np.hstack((color1, color2, color3))
        else:
            return np.hstack((color1, color2, color3))
    else:
        if vis==True:
            return resized, resized.ravel()
        else:
            return resized.ravel()
                        
def color_hist(img, nbins=32, vis=False):    #bins_range=(0, 256)
    # Compute the histogram of the color channels separately
    channel1_hist = np.histogram(img[:,:,0], bins=nbins)
    channel2_hist = np.histogram(img[:,:,1], bins=nbins)
    channel3_hist = np.histogram(img[:,:,2], bins=nbins)
    # Concatenate the histograms into a single feature vector
    hist_features = np.concatenate((channel1_hist[0], channel2_hist[0], channel3_hist[0]))
    if vis:
        return channel1_hist[0],channel2_hist[0],channel3_hist[0],hist_features
    return hist_features

# Define a function to return HOG features and visualization
def get_hog_features(img, orient, pix_per_cell, cell_per_block, 
                     vis=False, feature_vec=True):
    # Call with two outputs if vis==True
    if vis == True:
        features, hog_image = hog(img, orientations=orient, 
                                  pixels_per_cell=(pix_per_cell, pix_per_cell),
                                  cells_per_block=(cell_per_block, cell_per_block), 
                                  transform_sqrt=True, 
                                  visualise=vis, feature_vector=feature_vec, 
                                  block_norm='L2-Hys')
        return features, hog_image
    # Otherwise call with one output
    else:      
        features = hog(img, orientations=orient, 
                       pixels_per_cell=(pix_per_cell, pix_per_cell),
                       cells_per_block=(cell_per_block, cell_per_block), 
                       transform_sqrt=True, 
                       visualise=vis, feature_vector=feature_vec, 
                       block_norm='L2-Hys')
        return features
    
def image_feature(image,cspace,spatial_size,hist_bins,hog_cspace,hog_channel,
                  orient, pix_per_cell, cell_per_block):
    # apply color conversion if other than 'RGB'
    feature_image = convert_color(image, conv=cspace)

    # Get color features
    spatial_features = bin_spatial(feature_image, size=spatial_size)
    hist_features = color_hist(feature_image, nbins=hist_bins)

    # Call get_hog_features() with vis=False, feature_vec=True
    if hog_cspace != cspace:
        feature_image = convert_color(image, conv=hog_cspace)
    if hog_channel == "ALL":
        hog_features = []
        for channel in range(feature_image.shape[2]):
            hog_features.append(get_hog_features(feature_image[:,:,channel], 
                                orient, pix_per_cell, cell_per_block, 
                                vis=False, feature_vec=True))
        hog_features = np.ravel(hog_features)
    else :
        hog_features = get_hog_features(feature_image[:,:,hog_channel], 
                                orient, pix_per_cell, cell_per_block, 
                                vis=False, feature_vec=True)

    feat_concat = np.concatenate((spatial_features, hist_features, hog_features),axis=0)
    return feat_concat

# Define a function to extract features from a list of images
# Have this function call bin_spatial() and color_hist()
def maybe_extract_features(filename, imgs, 
                           cspace='RGB', hist_bins=32,
                           spatial_size=(16,16),
                           hog_cspace='RGB', hog_channel=0, 
                           orient=9, pix_per_cell=8, 
                           cell_per_block=2,
                           flipped=False,
                           force=False):
    if os.path.exists(filename) and not force:
        # You may override by setting force=True.
        print('%s already present - Skipping preprocessing. Loading pickle file instead.' \
              % (filename))
        try:
            print('Loading %s ...' % (filename))
            with open(filename, 'rb') as f:
                data = pickle.load(f)
                features = data['features']
                timeElapsed = data['timeElapsed']
            print('Loading done.')
        except Exception as e:
            print('Unable to extract data from', filename, ':', e)
    
    else:
        t=time.time()
        # Create a list to append feature vectors to
        features = []
        # Iterate through the list of images
        for file in imgs:
            # Read in each one by one
            image = cv2.imread(file)
            image = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
            feature = image_feature(image,cspace,spatial_size,hist_bins,hog_cspace,
                                    hog_channel,orient, pix_per_cell, cell_per_block)
            features.append(feature)
            if flipped:
                image_flipped = cv2.flip(image,1)
                feature_flipped = image_feature(image_flipped,cspace,spatial_size,
                                                hist_bins,hog_cspace,hog_channel,
                                                orient, pix_per_cell, cell_per_block)
                features.append(feature_flipped)
            
        t2 = time.time()
        timeElapsed = round(t2-t,2)
        print('Feature extraction done.')
        print('Pickling %s ...' % (filename))
        data={}
        data['features']=features
        data['timeElapsed']=timeElapsed
        try:
            with open(filename, 'wb') as f:
                pickle.dump(data, f, pickle.HIGHEST_PROTOCOL)
            print('Pickling done.')
        except Exception as e:
            print('Unable to save data to',  filename, ':', e)
    # Return list of feature vectors
    return features, timeElapsed

def visualize_bin_spatial(image, colorspace="RGB",spatial_size=(32,32)):
    color=convert_color(image, conv=colorspace)
    resized, color1, color2, color3, _ = bin_spatial(color, size=spatial_size, vis=True)
    fig = NewFigure(14,7)
    ax=plt.subplot2grid((2, 4), (0, 0), rowspan=2)
    plt.title("Original color image")
    plt.axis("on")
    plt.imshow(image,cmap=None)
    ax=DisplaySub(fig,2,4,2,resized[:,:,0],axis="on",
                  title=colorspace + " Channel 1, Size: " + str(spatial_size),
                  cmap="gray")
    ax=DisplaySub(fig,2,4,3,resized[:,:,1],axis="on",
                  title=colorspace + " Channel 2, Size: " + str(spatial_size),
                  cmap="gray")
    ax=DisplaySub(fig,2,4,4,resized[:,:,2],axis="on",
                  title=colorspace + " Channel 3, Size: " + str(spatial_size),
                  cmap="gray")
    plt.subplot(2,4,6)
    plt.plot(color1)
    plt.title('Channel 1 Spatial Bin')
    plt.subplot(2,4,7)
    plt.plot(color2)
    plt.title('Channel 2 Spatial Bin')
    plt.subplot(2,4,8)
    plt.plot(color3)
    plt.title('Channel 3 Spatial Bin')
    plt.show()
    
# Plot a figure with all three bar charts
def visualize_color_hist(image, colorspace="RGB",nbins=32):
    color=convert_color(image, conv=colorspace)
    hist_ch1, hist_ch2, hist_ch3, feature_vec = color_hist(image, nbins=nbins,vis=True)
    fig = NewFigure(14,7)
    ax=plt.subplot2grid((2, 4), (0, 0), rowspan=2)
    plt.title("Original color image")
    plt.axis("on")
    plt.imshow(image,cmap=None)
    ax=DisplaySub(fig,2,4,2,color[:,:,0],axis="on",title=colorspace + " Channel 1",cmap="gray")
    ax=DisplaySub(fig,2,4,3,color[:,:,1],axis="on",title=colorspace + " Channel 2",cmap="gray")
    ax=DisplaySub(fig,2,4,4,color[:,:,2],axis="on",title=colorspace + " Channel 3",cmap="gray")
    bin_cen_ = [np.round(k*(255/(2*nbins)),1) for k in range(2*nbins+1)]
    bin_cen=[bin_cen_[i] for i in range(1,2*nbins,2)]
    plt.subplot(246)
    plt.bar(bin_cen, hist_ch1, 255/nbins,edgecolor='k')
    plt.axis([-10,266,0,max(hist_ch1)*1.05])
    plt.title('Channel 1 Histogram')
    plt.subplot(247)
    plt.bar(bin_cen, hist_ch2, 255/nbins,edgecolor='k')
    plt.axis([-10,266,0,max(hist_ch2)*1.05])
    plt.title('Channel 2 Histogram')
    plt.subplot(248)
    plt.bar(bin_cen, hist_ch3, 255/nbins,edgecolor='k')
    plt.axis([-10,266,0,max(hist_ch3)*1.05])
    plt.title('Channel 3 Histogram')
    plt.show()
    
def visualize_hog_single(image,fig, NumRow, dispIdx, colorspace, channel):
    NumCol=3
    hog,vis=get_hog_features(image, orient, 
                             pix_per_cell, cell_per_block, 
                             vis=True, feature_vec=True)
    ax=DisplaySub(fig, NumRow, NumCol, dispIdx*NumCol+1,image,
                  title=str(colorspace)+ ' - Channel ' + str(channel+1), 
                  axis='on',cmap='gray')
    ax=DisplaySub(fig, NumRow, NumCol, dispIdx*NumCol+2,vis,
                  title='Hog Visualization',axis='on',cmap='gray')
    plt.subplot(NumRow,NumCol,dispIdx*NumCol+3)
    plt.plot(hog)
    plt.title('HOG feature vector')
    
def visualize_hog(image,colorspace,channel):
    color=convert_color(image,colorspace)
    
    if colorspace=="GRAY":
        f=NewFigure()
        visualize_hog_single(color,f, 1, 0)
    else:
        if channel!="ALL":
            f=NewFigure(18,6)
            visualize_hog_single(color[:,:,channel],f, 1, 0, colorspace, channel)
        else:
            f=NewFigure(12,12)
            for i in range(color.shape[2]):
                visualize_hog_single(color[:,:,i],f, color.shape[2]+1, i, colorspace, i)
    plt.show()

def maybe_gridsearchcv(filename, model, X, y, params,force=False):
    if os.path.exists(filename) and not force:
        # You may override by setting force=True.
        print('%s already present - Skipping model tuning. Loading pickle file instead.' \
              % (filename))
        try:
            print('Loading %s ...' % (filename))
            with open(filename, 'rb') as f:
                data = pickle.load(f)
                grid_obj = data['grid_obj']
                timeElapsed = data['timeElapsed']
            print('Loading done.')
        except Exception as e:
            print('Unable to extract data from', filename, ':', e)
    
    else:
        t=time.time()
        grid_obj = GridSearchCV(model,params,cv=5,scoring='accuracy')
        grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(X, y)
        t2 = time.time()
        timeElapsed=round(t2-t, 2)
        data={}
        data['grid_obj']=grid_obj
        data['timeElapsed']=timeElapsed
        try:
            with open(filename, 'wb') as f:
                pickle.dump(data, f, pickle.HIGHEST_PROTOCOL)
            print('Pickling done.')
        except Exception as e:
            print('Unable to save data to',  filename, ':', e)
    return grid_obj, timeElapsed

Multiscale sliding window¶

We will be implementing sliding window search in the image at two different scales, i.e. 1x and 2x.

However, instead of using window of two different sizes, we will be using the same 64x64 pixel window for both the 1x and 2x sliding window search.

For the 1x sliding window search, we will use the 64x64 pixel sliding window in the image at the original size. For the 2x sliding window search, we will use the 64x64 pixel sliding window in the image scaled by 0.5 in both width and height.

In [25]:
def multiscale_vis(image,
                   ystart, ystop,
                   xstart, xstop):
    cropped=image[ystart:ystop,xstart:xstop,:]
    imshape=cropped.shape

Optimizing sliding window search¶

In [28]:
def draw_sliding_windows(window, xstart, ystart, width, height):
    nx_steps=width//window
    ny_steps=height//window

    for xb in range(nx_steps):
        for yb in range(ny_steps):
            xpos = xb*window + xstart
            ypos = yb*window + ystart
            roi=Rectangle((xpos,ypos),window, window,fill=False,color='c',linewidth=2)
            ax.add_patch(roi)

Due to perspective projection of the camera, we know that cars appear smaller further down the horizon of the image. Hence, we can restrict the sliding window search of scale 1 near the horizon of the image.

The green rectangle below represents the region where the sliding window search of scale 1 took place. The cyan rectangles are the 64x64 pixel windows with 0% overlap to illustrate the size of the window without confusion. (Note: in actual implementation, we use overlap of 75%, hence, there will be more overlapping windows that it appears here.)

Efficient sliding window search¶

In order to speed up the processing time to achieve realtime performance, it would be useful to compute the HOG features once for each frame and then perform sub-sampling from the computed HOG feature map during the sliding window search.

The following function 'find_cars' performs such operations and returns windows which the SVM classifier recognizes as the class 'car'.

In [31]:
# Define a single function that can extract features using hog sub-sampling and make predictions
def find_cars(img, 
              ystart, ystop,
              xstart, xstop,
              scale, 
              model, X_scaler,
              colorspace, 
              hist_bins, spatial_size,
              hog_colorspace, hog_channel, 
              orient, pix_per_cell, cell_per_block, 
              cells_per_step=2,
              vis=False):
    if vis==True:
        draw_img = np.copy(img)
    
    img_tosearch = img[ystart:ystop,xstart:xstop,:]
    
    ctrans_tosearch = convert_color(img_tosearch, conv=colorspace)
    if hog_colorspace!=colorspace:
        hog_tosearch = convert_color(img_tosearch, conv=hog_colorspace)
    else:
        hog_tosearch = ctrans_tosearch
        
    if scale != 1:
        imshape = img_tosearch.shape
        ctrans_tosearch = cv2.resize(ctrans_tosearch, (np.int(imshape[1]/scale), np.int(imshape[0]/scale)))
        hog_tosearch = cv2.resize(hog_tosearch, (np.int(imshape[1]/scale), np.int(imshape[0]/scale)))
        
    # Define blocks and steps as above
    nxblocks = (hog_tosearch.shape[1] // pix_per_cell) - cell_per_block + 1
    nyblocks = (hog_tosearch.shape[0] // pix_per_cell) - cell_per_block + 1 
    nfeat_per_block = orient*cell_per_block**2
    
    # 64 was the orginal sampling rate, with 8 cells and 8 pix per cell
    window = 64
    nblocks_per_window = (window // pix_per_cell) - cell_per_block + 1
    nxsteps = (nxblocks - nblocks_per_window) // cells_per_step + 1
    nysteps = (nyblocks - nblocks_per_window) // cells_per_step + 1
    
    # Compute individual channel HOG features for the entire image
    ch1 = hog_tosearch[:,:,0]
    ch2 = hog_tosearch[:,:,1]
    ch3 = hog_tosearch[:,:,2]
    hog1 = get_hog_features(ch1, orient, pix_per_cell, cell_per_block, feature_vec=False)
    hog2 = get_hog_features(ch2, orient, pix_per_cell, cell_per_block, feature_vec=False)
    hog3 = get_hog_features(ch3, orient, pix_per_cell, cell_per_block, feature_vec=False)
    hog=[hog1,hog2,hog3]
    
    matches=[]
    for xb in range(nxsteps):
        for yb in range(nysteps):
            ypos = yb*cells_per_step
            xpos = xb*cells_per_step
            # Extract HOG for this patch
            if hog_channel == "ALL":
                hog_feat1 = hog[0][ypos:ypos+nblocks_per_window, xpos:xpos+nblocks_per_window].ravel() 
                hog_feat2 = hog[1][ypos:ypos+nblocks_per_window, xpos:xpos+nblocks_per_window].ravel() 
                hog_feat3 = hog[2][ypos:ypos+nblocks_per_window, xpos:xpos+nblocks_per_window].ravel() 
                hog_features = np.hstack((hog_feat1, hog_feat2, hog_feat3))
            else:
                hog_features = hog[hog_channel][ypos:ypos+nblocks_per_window, xpos:xpos+nblocks_per_window].ravel() 

            xleft = xpos*pix_per_cell
            ytop = ypos*pix_per_cell

            # Get color features
            subimg = cv2.resize(ctrans_tosearch[ytop:ytop+window, xleft:xleft+window], (64,64))
            spatial_features = bin_spatial(subimg, size=spatial_size)
            hist_features = color_hist(subimg, nbins=hist_bins)
            
            # Scale features and make a prediction
            test_features = X_scaler.transform(np.hstack((spatial_features,
                                                          hist_features,
                                                          hog_features)).reshape(1, -1))
            test_prediction = model.predict(test_features)
            
            if test_prediction == 1:
                xleft_draw = np.int(xleft*scale)
                ytop_draw = np.int(ytop*scale)
                win_draw = np.int(window*scale)
                
                x1=xleft_draw+xstart
                y1=ytop_draw+ystart
                x2=x1+win_draw
                y2=y1+win_draw
                matches.append(((x1,y1),(x2,y2)))
                if vis==True:
                    cv2.rectangle(draw_img,(x1,y1),(x2,y2),(0,0,255),6) 
    if vis==True:            
        return matches, draw_img
    else:            
        return matches

Combine overlapping detections and remove false positives¶

We use the concept of a heatmap for combining overlapping detections and remove false positives. From the list of bounding boxes for the detections in the image, we add "heat" (+=1) for all pixels within windows where a positive detection is reported by the classifier.

The "hot" parts (high valued) of the heatmap are where the cars are, and by imposing a threshold, we can reject areas affected by false positives. Once we have a thresholded heatmap, we will use the label() function from scipy.ndimage.measurements to figure out how many cars we have in each frame and which pixels belong to which cars.

For each blob of thresholded heatmap, a bounding box is returned to represent the position of the detected car.

In [36]:
def add_heat(heatmap, bbox_list):
    # Iterate through list of bboxes
    for box in bbox_list:
        # Add += 1 for all pixels inside each bbox
        # Assuming each "box" takes the form ((x1, y1), (x2, y2))
        heatmap[box[0][1]:box[1][1], box[0][0]:box[1][0]] += 1

    # Return updated heatmap
    return heatmap

heatmap=np.zeros((image.shape[0],image.shape[1]))
heatmap=add_heat(heatmap, found)
f=NewFigure()
ax=DisplaySub(f,1,1,1,heatmap,axis='on',cmap='hot')
In [37]:
def apply_threshold(heatmap, threshold):
    # Zero out pixels below the threshold
    heatmap[heatmap <= threshold] = 0
    # Return thresholded map
    return heatmap

thres=2
heatmap_thres = apply_threshold(heatmap, thres)
labels = label(heatmap_thres)
print(labels[1], 'cars found')
f=NewFigure()
ax=DisplaySub(f,1,1,1,labels[0],axis='on',cmap='gray')

2 cars found
In [38]:
def get_labeled_bboxes(img, labels):
    bboxes=[]
    # Iterate through all detected cars
    for car_number in range(1, labels[1]+1):
        # Find pixels with each car_number label value
        nonzero = (labels[0] == car_number).nonzero()
        # Identify x and y values of those pixels
        nonzeroy = np.array(nonzero[0])
        nonzerox = np.array(nonzero[1])
        # Define a bounding box based on min/max x and y
        x = np.min(nonzerox)
        y = np.min(nonzeroy)
        w = np.max(nonzerox) - x
        h = np.max(nonzeroy) - y
        bbox = (x,y,w,h)
        bboxes.append(bbox)
    # Return the image
    return bboxes

def draw_bboxes(img, bboxes):
    for bbox in bboxes:
        # Draw the box on the image
        cv2.rectangle(img, 
                      (bbox[0], bbox[1]),
                      (bbox[2]+bbox[0], bbox[3]+bbox[1]), 
                      (0,0,255), 6)
    # Return the image
    return img

bboxes = get_labeled_bboxes(np.copy(image), labels)
draw_img = draw_bboxes(np.copy(image), bboxes)
f=NewFigure()
ax=DisplaySub(f,1,1,1,draw_img,axis='on')

Video implementation¶

The project video is a video file with frame rate of 25 fps. However, for our purpose of realtime vehicle detection, it is not necessary to have such fine resolution in time since human capability in recognizing vehicles during driving also cannot reach this level.

For practical reasons, we will only process the video at frame rate of 5 fps by taking every fifth frame of the video stream. For intermediate frames, we will visualize them with the result from the last processed frame.

In addition, to further reduce the false positives, smoothing of detected bounding boxes across multiple frames is implemented. Heatmap from the last 8 processed frames are stored and an average heatmap is computed. The averaged heatmap is then thresholded at value of 1.3.

In [39]:
# Define a class to store the heatmap result from last n frame
class HeatObject():
    def __init__(self, n=5):
        self.iter = 0
        # n iterations to keep
        self.n = n
        # heatmap deque list
        self.heat = deque()
        # last result
        self.last_output = []
In [40]:
def process_image(im):
    if heatObj.iter%5 == 0:
        found1=find_cars(im, 
                        ystart1, ystop1, 
                        xstart1, xstop1,
                        scale1, 
                        svc, X_scaler, 
                        colorspace, 
                        hist_bins, spatial_size,
                        hog_colorspace, hog_channel,
                        orient, pix_per_cell, cell_per_block, 
                        cells_per_step=cells_per_step1)
        found2=find_cars(im, 
                        ystart2, ystop2, 
                        xstart2, xstop2,
                        scale2, 
                        svc, X_scaler, 
                        colorspace, 
                        hist_bins, spatial_size,
                        hog_colorspace, hog_channel,
                        orient, pix_per_cell, cell_per_block, 
                        cells_per_step=cells_per_step2)
        found3=find_cars(im, 
                        ystart3, ystop3, 
                        xstart3, xstop3,
                        scale3, 
                        svc, X_scaler, 
                        colorspace, 
                        hist_bins, spatial_size,
                        hog_colorspace, hog_channel,
                        orient, pix_per_cell, cell_per_block, 
                        cells_per_step=cells_per_step3)
        found=found1+found2+found3
        heatmap=np.zeros((im.shape[0],im.shape[1]))
        heatmap=add_heat(heatmap, found)

        heatObj.heat.append(heatmap)
        if (heatObj.iter//5 >= heatObj.n):
            heatObj.heat.popleft()

        heat_cummulated=np.zeros_like(heatObj.heat[0])
        for h in heatObj.heat:
            heat_cummulated+=h
        heat_average = heat_cummulated.astype(np.float64) / len(heatObj.heat)

        heatmap_thres = apply_threshold(heat_average, thres)   

        labels = label(heatmap_thres)   
        bboxes = get_labeled_bboxes(im, labels)
        heatObj.last_output = bboxes
    else:
        bboxes = heatObj.last_output
    result = draw_bboxes(np.copy(im),bboxes)
    
    heatObj.iter += 1
    return result
